Russia’s war is going nowhere. It is becoming weaker every day. https://t.co/TRcLbOR2yb', '36432c6b2e4b006d7182a50785412f3ddfb7faafc14edffbecdd3023c092e5eb', -7971716927459842820, NULL, 'twitter', 0, NULL, 'x.com', 'https://x.com/Braze_Baiba/status/2048690572139831358', NULL, '2026-04-27 22:55:28', 42, 'en', '2026-04-27T09:07:49+00:00', 0, NULL, NULL, '2026-04-27 23:10:40', 1, 7, 26);
INSERT INTO documents (id, content, content_hash, simhash, source_id, platform, is_auto_caption, near_dupe_of, source_domain, source_url, archive_path, scraped_at, word_count, language, published_at, is_paywall, summary, title, reviewed_at, reply_count, retweet_count, favorite_count) VALUES (27117, 'Spain''s Significant Support for Criminal Regimes - Now and Relatively Recently. How Justified Are the US Accusations and Threats to Expel Spain from NATO?

Just how unreliable of a NATO partner can Spain itself be? At this moment, we must remember the less publicly known, yet highly significant, Spanish support for Russia and the regime of Syrian dictator Bashar al-Assad in 2014-2015. While European countries acted in solidarity to impose sanctions against Russia after the annexation of Crimea in 2014, suffering substantial losses in the process, Spain openly collaborated with... the Russian Navy, supporting its espionage activities. This made a vital contribution to Russia''s foreign policy victory in the Middle East, the stabilization of Assad''s bloody regime, and the subsequent repressions, including mass murders committed against his own people. This sparked a massive refugee crisis in Europe. Furthermore, the Assad regime continued to destabilize the Middle East, actively supporting various radical terrorist groups.

Between 2014 and 2015, in the Spanish-owned North African port of Ceuta, located across the Strait of Gibraltar, Russian naval vessels replenished their fuel, food, and water supplies at least 13 times, including a submarine in at least one instance. It must be noted that this occurred at the exact same time Russia was occupying Ukraine''s Crimea. A large portion of this military transport was heading to Syria, where it was extensively utilized for the objectives of the Assad and Putin regimes. All of this happened with the consent of the Spanish government.

Back then, in 2015, despite Russian aggression against Ukraine, the cooperation between the Spanish and Russian navies continued. Alex Calvo, a prominent analyst at the US Jamestown Foundation, pointed out in a comprehensive article that the Russian Navy had enjoyed Spanish hospitality and support at least 12 times (other sources say 14). The reaction from Great Britain was particularly indignant, as it was forced to watch how, right under the nose of its port of Gibraltar, Spain serviced and permitted the Russian submarine Novorossiysk to dock for three days. Russian media also reported that the warship Yaroslav Mudry and the Russian Baltic Fleet''s replenishment oiler Kola received similar servicing.

The greatest outrage was sparked by the news that the Spanish hosted and supplied the Russian "scientific research" vessel Yantar with fuel and food. Western allies consider this ship to be a highly dangerous, high-tech spy vessel. Despite this, Spain warmly welcomed this incredibly dangerous spy ship into its port, refueled it, and replenished its food supplies so that it could once again resume its mission... to spy. Of course, who was this special Russian warship spying on? NATO countries. And the Spanish government openly supported this hostile action.

At the time, this collaboration between Russia and Spain was very likely crucial to Putin''s Russia''s foreign policy achievement - stabilizing Assad''s dictatorial regime. Russia''s capacity to deliver military aid to Assad via air transport was quite limited. Serious, decisively large deliveries of military equipment required maritime transport. The transit support provided by Spanish-controlled ports was highly advantageous for Russia. In this way, Spain provided substantial support to the criminal regimes of Putin and Assad.

How could this happen? At the time, Spain cynically exploited legal loopholes to aid the Kremlin. The Ceuta enclave, located in North Africa directly opposite the strategically vital Gibraltar, has a port that is formally and legally situated outside the North Atlantic collective defense area defined in Article 6 of the NATO Treaty. Furthermore, the early EU sanctions (2014–2015) did not explicitly prohibit such warship visits or the provision of port services. This "grey area" allowed Spain to act formally within the law, even though its allies rightfully perceived it as an action contrary to the spirit of alliance solidarity.

Following immense diplomatic pressure, Spain ceased this practice in late 2016. However, significant, decisive assistance had already been provided to Russia and the Assad regime-Russia regained its international influence and a strategically vital military gateway to Africa, while the Assad regime was able to continue slaughtering its own people, destabilizing peace in the Middle East, broadly supporting terrorist networks, and critically flooding Europe with refugees.

Indeed - everything suggests that NATO member state Spain has extensive experience collaborating with the Russian military and intelligence services, providing significant support to criminal regimes. This, of course, inevitably raises serious questions about Spain''s reliability as an EU and NATO member state.

The only question is whether this crucial information, which provides necessary context, will be shared with you by @DeutscheWelle, @BBCPolitics, @srfnews, @cnni, @InsiderEng, @RFERL, @VilaWeb_EN, @POLITICOEurope, @nytopinion, @elonmusk, @Independent', 'a88aa099072a2e633d8a902b67becb62ff1b21e2bc4db16967d8ed0822897d40', -8976538576388942609, NULL, 'twitter', 0, NULL, 'x.com', 'https://x.com/OttoOzols/status/2048778178986971216', NULL, '2026-04-27 22:55:38', 756, 'en', '2026-04-27T14:55:56+00:00', 0, NULL, NULL, '2026-04-27 23:13:11', 0, 0, 0);
